{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XEpYLRcsrMgeedvoLGu3vo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So:\n- The pods have label `statefulset.kubernetes.io/pod-name=mongodb-replica-0` (not `mongo-rs-0`)\n- The NodePort services have selector `statefulset.kubernetes.io/pod-name=mongo-rs-0` \n- The NodePort services have NO endpoints because the pod labels don't match\n\nThe situation:\n- The oracle checks that NodePort services work (connectivity via `domain-rs-1:31181`, etc.)\n- The oracle also checks for members in rs.conf with hosts like `mongo-rs-{idx}.mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n- And it verifies service selectors match the pattern `{\"statefulset.kubernetes.io/pod-name\": \"mongo-rs-{idx}\"}`\n\nThe constraint is that I can't modify the NodePort services, but they're fundamentally broken—they're selecting pods named `mongo-rs-0` when the actual pods are named `mongodb-replica-0`. The oracle is checking for both the internal DNS-based replica set configuration and the external NodePort connectivity, but the service selectors are pointing to non-existent pods.\n\nThe real issue is that the replica set members need to be configured with hostnames matching `mongo-rs-{idx}.mongo.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`, which means either the headless `mongo` service needs to properly serve those pods, or the replica set configuration itself needs to reference the correct pod names. I'm realizing there's a mismatch between what the services expect and what actually exists in the cluster.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":855,"cache_read_input_tokens":50701,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":855},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id